SIMPLE: skipper
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Skipper
<hw>Skip"per</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who,
or that which, skips.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A young, thoughtless person.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The saury (<spn>Scomberesox
saurus</spn>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The cheese maggot. See <cref>Cheese fly</cref>,
under <er>Cheese</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of
small butterflies of the family <fam>Hesperiadae</fam>; -- so called
from their peculiar short, jerking flight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skipper</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Skipper
<hw>Skip"per</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>schipper</ets>. See
<er>Shipper</er>, and <er>Ship</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The master of a fishing or small trading vessel;
hence, the master, or captain, of any vessel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A ship boy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Congreve.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skippet</ent>⟦br⟧
